04577nam a22005535i 9780822390596DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20072007ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223905967 a10.1515/97808223905962doi  a(DE-B1597)552702  a(OCoLC)1224278174  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aGE199.B6bH63 2007 7aHIS0330002bisacsh1 aHochstetler, Kathryn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGreening Brazil :bEnvironmental Activism in State and Society /cMargaret E. Keck, Kathryn Hochstetler. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b5 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tlist of tables -- tpreface -- tlist of acronyms and organizations -- tIntroduction -- t1 Building Environmental Institutions National Environmental Politics and Policy -- t2 National Environmental Activism The Changing Terms of Engagement -- t3 From Protest to Project The Third Wave of Environmental Activism -- t4 Amazônia -- t5 From Pollution Control to Sustainable Cities -- tConclusion -- tappendix: list of interviews -- tnotes -- tbibliography -- tindex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGreening Brazil challenges the claim that environmentalism came to Brazil from abroad. Two political scientists, Kathryn Hochstetler and Margaret E. Keck, retell the story of environmentalism in Brazil from the inside out, analyzing the extensive efforts within the country to save its natural environment, and the interplay of those efforts with transnational environmentalism. The authors trace Brazil's complex environmental politics as they have unfolded over time, from their mid-twentieth-century conservationist beginnings to the contemporary development of a distinctive socio-environmentalism meant to address ecological destruction and social injustice simultaneously. Hochstetler and Keck argue that explanations of Brazilian environmentalism-and environmentalism in the global South generally-must take into account the way that domestic political processes shape environmental reform efforts.The authors present a multilevel analysis encompassing institutions and individuals within the government-at national, state, and local levels-as well as the activists, interest groups, and nongovernmental organizations that operate outside formal political channels. They emphasize the importance of networks linking committed actors in the government bureaucracy with activists in civil society. Portraying a gradual process marked by periods of rapid advance, Hochstetler and Keck show how political opportunities have arisen from major political transformations such as the transition to democracy and from critical events, including the well-publicized murders of environmental activists in 1988 and 2004. Rather than view foreign governments and organizations as the instigators of environmental policy change in Brazil, the authors point to their importance at key moments as sources of leverage and support.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aEnvironmentalismxPolitical aspectszBrazil. 0aEnvironmentalismzBrazil. 0aGreen movementzBrazil. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh1 aKeck, Margaret E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822390596zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822390596423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822390596.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL 